and then have that version
of the written language

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:52.140
be accepted by everyone.

00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:53.820
It's an extraordinary thing, right?

00:37:53.820 --> 00:37:56.021
In England, it's largely
a matter of Shakespeare

00:37:56.021 --> 00:37:59.100
or the King James Bible.

00:37:59.100 --> 00:38:02.040
But, you know, so the language question,

00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:03.420
what's the answer, right?

00:38:03.420 --> 00:38:05.310
So some places it might seem
more or less obvious, like,

00:38:05.310 --> 00:38:07.946
okay, you take a version of
French or version of English,

00:38:07.946 --> 00:38:10.890
but in Ukraine, what's the answer?

00:38:10.890 --> 00:38:13.380
What's the answer to the
language question in Ukraine?

00:38:13.380 --> 00:38:14.820
You have old church Slavonic,

00:38:14.820 --> 00:38:16.380
which is still around somewhere.

00:38:16.380 --> 00:38:18.900
You have the Ukrainian vernacular,

00:38:18.900 --> 00:38:21.203
which is perfectly well exists.

00:38:21.203 --> 00:38:23.640
And you have Polish.

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:25.410
And all these things are possible, right?

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:27.900
These are all possible answers
to the language question.

00:38:27.900 --> 00:38:29.040
But the way it's answered,

00:38:29.040 --> 00:38:30.570
the actual answer to the language question

00:38:30.570 --> 00:38:34.020
in Ukraine is Polish, as I said before.

00:38:34.020 --> 00:38:36.990
So people start writing in a language

00:38:36.990 --> 00:38:39.420
which isn't an ancient
language, which is not Greek,

00:38:39.420 --> 00:38:42.750
it's not old church Slavonic,
it's not Latin, it's Polish.

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:45.240
But this answer to the language question

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:49.290
is fundamentally different from
the other answers elsewhere.

00:38:49.290 --> 00:38:53.280
If the answer to the language
question in Poland is Polish,

00:38:53.280 --> 00:38:55.440
that means suddenly everybody
has the same, not everybody,

00:38:55.440 --> 00:38:57.390
but many people have the same language,

00:38:57.390 --> 00:38:58.590
top to bottom, right?

00:38:58.590 --> 00:38:59.910
The nobles and the peasants

00:38:59.910 --> 00:39:01.470
can be speaking the same language.

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:02.490
In France, the same.

00:39:02.490 --> 00:39:03.720
England, the same,

00:39:03.720 --> 00:39:05.100
Germany the same.

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:06.780
But in Ukraine, if the answer

00:39:06.780 --> 00:39:09.120
to the language question is Polish,

00:39:09.120 --> 00:39:12.240
then suddenly roughly one to two,

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:14.790
maybe three percent of the
population has one language,

00:39:14.790 --> 00:39:19.230
and 97% and 98% has another.

00:39:19.230 --> 00:39:22.200
That's a very different social outcome,

00:39:22.200 --> 00:39:23.100
very different social outcome.

00:39:23.100 --> 00:39:25.050
So the language question
always gets answered

00:39:25.050 --> 00:39:26.730
in terms of the modern language,

00:39:26.730 --> 00:39:27.960
but it doesn't always get answered

00:39:27.960 --> 00:39:29.460
in terms of the vernacular, right?

00:39:29.460 --> 00:39:31.140
So that's one thing which is very dramatic

00:39:31.140 --> 00:39:31.973
about the situation.

00:39:31.973 --> 00:39:34.800
Secondly, which is very
dramatic, is religion.

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:36.690
So again, while I'm telling you

00:39:36.690 --> 00:39:39.000
about the Czerwinsk Privilege,

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:40.789
while I'm telling you
about these Polish details,

00:39:40.789 --> 00:39:43.200
the Reformation is going on.

00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:45.390
And the Reformation is
going on also in Poland.

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:48.060
And in Poland in the 16th century,

00:39:48.060 --> 00:39:50.850
most of the nobility
actually goes Protestant.

00:39:50.850 --> 00:39:52.080
So like during the period,

00:39:52.080 --> 00:39:53.910
which the Poles find themselves
find the most interesting,

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:56.280
which is the 16th century,
they had a Lithuanian dynasty,

00:39:56.280 --> 00:39:58.020
and they had a Protestant parliament,

00:39:58.020 --> 00:39:59.640
which is just worth remembering,

00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:01.390
small talk for your Polish friends.

00:40:02.430 --> 00:40:06.690
And in Ukraine, you also
have the Reformation.

00:40:06.690 --> 00:40:09.870
But in the Reformation in Ukraine

00:40:09.870 --> 00:40:12.840
is going to involve Protestants,

00:40:12.840 --> 00:40:15.630
it's going to involve Catholics
in the Counter-Reformation,

00:40:15.630 --> 00:40:18.690
but the population is
mostly Orthodox, right?

00:40:18.690 --> 00:40:21.450
This is Rus, this is Eastern Christianity.

00:40:21.450 --> 00:40:24.480
So you have a Reformation
and a Counter-Reformation,

00:40:24.480 --> 00:40:27.090
which are overlaying onto this population,

00:40:27.090 --> 00:40:28.440
which is mainly Orthodox.

00:40:28.440 --> 00:40:30.870
And the Reformation
and Counter-Reformation

00:40:30.870 --> 00:40:32.430
are gonna go through
all kinds of gymnastics.

00:40:32.430 --> 00:40:33.870
And the elite families are gonna,

00:40:33.870 --> 00:40:35.100
they're first gonna go Protestant,

00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:36.450
and then they're gonna go Catholic.

00:40:36.450 --> 00:40:38.082
And it's all very interesting.

00:40:38.082 --> 00:40:40.140
But at the end of the
day, what happens is that

00:40:40.140 --> 00:40:41.894
after about three generations of this,

00:40:41.894 --> 00:40:44.220
you're going to have a top layer

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:47.940
of the Ukrainian population,
generally the richest nobles.

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:51.088
The people who also own a lot
of land and a lot of serfs,

00:40:51.088 --> 00:40:52.863
they're gonna be Roman Catholic,

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:55.020
and they're also gonna be the same people

00:40:55.020 --> 00:40:56.760
who are speaking Polish, right?

00:40:56.760 --> 00:40:58.770
So that's the second thing which happens.

00:40:58.770 --> 00:41:01.263
There's a new religious question.

00:41:01.263 --> 00:41:04.380
And then the final thing
which is going to happen,

00:41:04.380 --> 00:41:07.683
which I've already suggested,
is the social question.

00:41:09.330 --> 00:41:13.110
Suddenly, Poles can own land in Ukraine.

00:41:13.110 --> 00:41:15.420
So if you're an ambitious Polish noble

00:41:15.420 --> 00:41:18.570
with maybe not enough
land, you go east, right?

00:41:18.570 --> 00:41:22.530
And you go east with European
land management practices,

00:41:22.530 --> 00:41:24.330
and you go east with your

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:27.480
almost certainly Jewish
manager, right, and his family,

00:41:27.480 --> 00:41:31.747
and you go off and you
colonize and you make money.

00:41:31.747 --> 00:41:35.310
And then the local Ukrainians
who see what you were doing,

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:36.750
the local Ukrainian nobles,

00:41:36.750 --> 00:41:38.550
they immediately copy what you're doing.

00:41:38.550 --> 00:41:39.930
They also insert their peasants.

00:41:39.930 --> 00:41:41.730
They also take a surplus.

00:41:41.730 --> 00:41:44.310
They also sell it up to the
Vistula River into Europe

00:41:44.310 --> 00:41:46.456
and the wider world if they can.

00:41:46.456 --> 00:41:51.456
And so the result of this is that you have

00:41:51.780 --> 00:41:55.650
suddenly a population
which is ever less free,

00:41:55.650 --> 00:41:58.380
which enserfed, which
is bound to the land.

00:41:58.380 --> 00:42:00.810
And you have a noble
class, which is small.

00:42:00.810 --> 00:42:02.460
So I said in Poland as a whole,

00:42:02.460 --> 00:42:04.842
10% of the population is noble, yes.

00:42:04.842 --> 00:42:06.540
In some places, more.

00:42:06.540 --> 00:42:09.090
Mazovia, it's like 25%, right?

00:42:09.090 --> 00:42:11.070
So basically in Mazovia,
if you're not a noble,

00:42:11.070 --> 00:42:12.360
you have some explaining to do.

00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:16.503
But, in Ukraine, 1%, 2%, okay?

00:42:17.964 --> 00:42:22.440
So 1%, 2% of the population owns the land,

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:27.172
controls much of the
rest of the population,

00:42:27.172 --> 00:42:31.050
largely speaks Polish, and
is largely Roman Catholic.

00:42:31.050 --> 00:42:35.310
And that whole transformation
takes place very quickly.

00:42:35.310 --> 00:42:40.310
Three generations from
about 1569 to the 1640s.

00:42:40.380 --> 00:42:42.300
That's the Polish connection.

00:42:42.300 --> 00:42:45.540
So, on the one side Polish connection,

00:42:45.540 --> 00:42:46.743
very beautiful, right?

00:42:48.300 --> 00:42:51.330
The Polish connection means variety.

00:42:51.330 --> 00:42:54.030
The Polish connection
means the Renaissance.

00:42:54.030 --> 00:42:56.130
The Polish connection means a whole lot

00:42:56.130 --> 00:42:58.680
of really interesting
theological disputes.

00:42:58.680 --> 00:43:01.890
The Polish connection means
that the Ukrainian clerics

00:43:01.890 --> 00:43:05.291
start their own academies and use Greek,

00:43:05.291 --> 00:43:07.740
force themselves to learn
Greek, which they'd been,

00:43:07.740 --> 00:43:09.510
you know, lazy about for
the previous six centuries.

00:43:09.510 --> 00:43:11.850
But now they do it and they learn Latin,

00:43:11.850 --> 00:43:14.010
and they learn Polish,
and they learn French.

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:17.413
And you know, and they become
some most interesting debaters

00:43:17.413 --> 00:43:19.830
because they have a lot, frankly,
they have a lot to handle.

00:43:19.830 --> 00:43:20.970
They have to handle the Reformation

00:43:20.970 --> 00:43:22.320
and the Counter-Reformation.

00:43:22.320 --> 00:43:24.867
They also have to handle after 1596,

00:43:24.867 --> 00:43:27.030
something called the Union of Brest,

00:43:27.030 --> 00:43:29.280
which is an attempt to bring the Catholic

00:43:29.280 --> 00:43:31.410
and the Orthodox churches together.

00:43:31.410 --> 00:43:32.430
They have a lot to talk about,

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:34.362
and they learn how to do it, right?

00:43:34.362 --> 00:43:37.380
The Polish connection means the Baroque.

00:43:37.380 --> 00:43:39.783
It means fabulous architecture, right?

00:43:42.014 --> 00:43:44.250
The Saint Sophia, as
it stands today in Kyiv

00:43:44.250 --> 00:43:46.976
is not the same one, which was built sadly

00:43:46.976 --> 00:43:49.050
in the 11th century.

00:43:49.050 --> 00:43:50.940
It's a kind of Baroque reconstruction,

00:43:50.940 --> 00:43:52.650
and it's very beautiful.

00:43:52.650 --> 00:43:54.000
And there are lots of churches in Ukraine

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:55.980
that are very beautiful,
but they're in a kind

00:43:55.980 --> 00:43:59.430
of Orthodox Baroque style, right?

00:43:59.430 --> 00:44:01.410
So the, the Polish connection
is very interesting.

00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:02.340
It's very beautiful.

00:44:02.340 --> 00:44:06.960
It's also hugely polarizing
because it puts a small number

00:44:06.960 --> 00:44:10.320
of people with one
language and one religion,

00:44:10.320 --> 00:44:13.350
and who have property rights
against a much larger group

00:44:13.350 --> 00:44:16.350
of people who have none
of those three people,

00:44:16.350 --> 00:44:18.420
which leads us to the Cassocks.

00:44:18.420 --> 00:44:23.420
So, the Cassocks are free people

00:44:23.858 --> 00:44:26.940
who manage to escape this system.

00:44:26.940 --> 00:44:30.570
They escape the system in which either you

00:44:30.570 --> 00:44:32.640
are a noble or a serf, right?

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:34.410
That's the Polish system.

00:44:34.410 --> 00:44:37.950
They escape that system by
going into the steppe, right,

00:44:37.950 --> 00:44:41.343
into the steppe into what's
now the southeast of Ukraine.

00:44:42.210 --> 00:44:45.030
They have their headquarters
and what they call the Sich

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:48.150
in the middle of the
Dniepr River, they farm,

00:44:48.150 --> 00:44:51.156
they fish, and they raid.

00:44:51.156 --> 00:44:52.830
They raid the Crimean Khanate,

00:44:52.830 --> 00:44:54.000
which we're gonna talk about.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.793
Sometimes they even try to raid Istanbul.

00:45:00.030 --> 00:45:02.643
And they survive by being out of reach.

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:06.390
They are at the fringes
though of the Polish system,

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:08.400
and they understand the Polish system,

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:12.870
and many of them are educated
by some of them anyway,

00:45:12.870 --> 00:45:17.850
like Bohdan Khmelnytsky, they're
educated by Jesuits, right?

00:45:17.850 --> 00:45:19.590
They know the Polish system

00:45:19.590 --> 00:45:23.070
and they have the idea of
rights, very important idea.

00:45:23.070 --> 00:45:24.630
They have the idea of rights.

00:45:24.630 --> 00:45:28.120
They have the idea that if we were nobles,

00:45:28.120 --> 00:45:30.960
we would have rights, right?

00:45:30.960 --> 00:45:33.660
And the Cossacks wanna
be in the Polish system,

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:35.280
but they're not allowed
into the Polish system

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:36.840
because the existing Polish nobility

00:45:36.840 --> 00:45:38.580
won't let them into the Polish system.

00:45:38.580 --> 00:45:41.250
So there's a compromise, which is struck,

00:45:41.250 --> 00:45:44.580
which is called being
a registered Cossack.

00:45:44.580 --> 00:45:47.280
So, there was a list of
a few thousand Cossacks

00:45:47.280 --> 00:45:50.250
who had some kind of
status in the Polish state,

00:45:50.250 --> 00:45:53.070
and then the rest of them were
called unregistered Cossacks,

00:45:53.070 --> 00:45:55.920
and they had no kind of
status in the Polish state.

00:45:55.920 --> 00:45:58.200
Every time Poland wanted to fight a war,

00:45:58.200 --> 00:46:00.750
the Cossacks suddenly
became very important.

00:46:00.750 --> 00:46:02.520
And this, by the way, was the period

00:46:02.520 --> 00:46:05.880
when the Poles were
extraordinarily successful

00:46:05.880 --> 00:46:07.650
on the battlefield, late 16th century,

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:11.370
early 17th century, when they
were defeating the Ottomans

00:46:11.370 --> 00:46:13.140
and they were defeating the Russians.

00:46:13.140 --> 00:46:15.480
In the early 17th century circa 1620,

00:46:15.480 --> 00:46:17.610
Poland is bigger than it ever will be,

00:46:17.610 --> 00:46:19.410
ever will be before or again.

00:46:19.410 --> 00:46:21.000
And that's when the Cossacks

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:23.992
are essentially serving as infantry.

00:46:23.992 --> 00:46:27.360
And the Polish nobility
is serving as cavalry.

00:46:27.360 --> 00:46:29.752
And they fight
extraordinarily well together.

00:46:29.752 --> 00:46:31.800
It's not a combination you would wish

00:46:31.800 --> 00:46:33.720
to face on the battlefield.

00:46:33.720 --> 00:46:37.620
But in 1648, this all breaks up.

00:46:37.620 --> 00:46:39.690
And you've heard some about this already.

00:46:39.690 --> 00:46:43.560
The underlying reasons
are what I talked about,

00:46:43.560 --> 00:46:48.560
the social, religious, and
linguistic differences.

00:46:48.990 --> 00:46:51.270
The precipitating reason has

00:46:51.270 --> 00:46:53.100
to do with the Cossacks themselves

00:46:53.100 --> 00:46:54.660
and whether or not Cossacks

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:56.520
are part of the Polish state or not.

00:46:56.520 --> 00:46:59.640
In particular, this guy
whose name I probably forget

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:02.457
to write down, write
down Khmelnytsky Bohdan.

00:47:12.510 --> 00:47:15.880
He has a claim which has to
do with his wife and property.

00:47:15.880 --> 00:47:19.740
And he's unable to get his
claim through the Polish courts.

00:47:19.740 --> 00:47:22.710
And at least, in legend,
the king laughs at him,

00:47:22.710 --> 00:47:26.002
you know, and he naturally
thinks, if I were a Polish noble,

00:47:26.002 --> 00:47:28.230
I would have access to the Polish courts.

00:47:28.230 --> 00:47:31.020
And he doesn't, and so he does what you do

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:32.850
when you don't have access to the law,

00:47:32.850 --> 00:47:34.650
which is that he rebels.

00:47:34.650 --> 00:47:38.850
But he rebels at a
time, this is the 1640s,

00:47:38.850 --> 00:47:41.970
at a time when the Cossacks
were all gathered anyway

00:47:41.970 --> 00:47:43.830
on the field for what was going

00:47:43.830 --> 00:47:45.780
to be a war against the Ottoman Empire.

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:48.180
And instead of fighting
against the Ottoman Empire,

00:47:48.180 --> 00:47:52.170
Khmelnytsky rouses them to
fight against the Poles.

00:47:52.170 --> 00:47:56.730
This happens at a time
when the Polish king dies,

00:47:56.730 --> 00:47:59.820
which means that there's
a while when the Cossacks

00:47:59.820 --> 00:48:01.789
have a great deal of
success on the battlefield

00:48:01.789 --> 00:48:03.630
fighting whom?

00:48:03.630 --> 00:48:04.890
This is important.

00:48:04.890 --> 00:48:09.510
Fighting generally the Polish
speaking Roman Catholic,

00:48:09.510 --> 00:48:11.340
Ukrainian nobility, right?

00:48:11.340 --> 00:48:12.960
This is largely a, this is not how it

00:48:12.960 --> 00:48:14.280
is in the Ukrainian textbooks,

00:48:14.280 --> 00:48:17.220
but this is largely a
Ukrainian-Ukrainian Civil War.

00:48:17.220 --> 00:48:18.180
At least at the beginning.

00:48:18.180 --> 00:48:20.724
It's the Cossacks against the Ukrainized,

00:48:20.724 --> 00:48:23.250
the Polandized Roman Catholic

00:48:23.250 --> 00:48:25.860
Polish-speaking local Ukrainian nobility,

00:48:25.860 --> 00:48:27.900
until the Polish army eventually shows up

00:48:27.900 --> 00:48:29.584
and turns the tide.

00:48:29.584 --> 00:48:32.280
When the Polish army shows
up and turns the tide,

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:33.900
we have a very fateful moment.

00:48:33.900 --> 00:48:36.450
And the very fateful
moment is that the Cossacks

00:48:36.450 --> 00:48:38.430
have to seek an ally.

00:48:38.430 --> 00:48:40.950
Up until about that time, their ally had

00:48:40.950 --> 00:48:44.313
been the Crimean Tatars,
the Crimean Khanate.

00:48:45.153 --> 00:48:50.153
As of 1654, the Crimean
Khanate has withdrawn,

00:48:50.561 --> 00:48:53.640
the Cossacks are losing
to the Polish state.

00:48:53.640 --> 00:48:55.290
And so they need an ally.

00:48:55.290 --> 00:48:59.280
And for an ally, they
find this fairly exotic

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:00.990
and unknown to them state,

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:02.220
which we've talked about a little bit.

00:49:02.220 --> 00:49:03.053
And we'll talk about more

00:49:03.053 --> 00:49:05.370
in the next lecture, which is Muscovy.

00:49:05.370 --> 00:49:07.520
And after that, everything
changes, thanks.

